      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Analyzing primary sources enables learners to understand the varied motivations behind Texican actions and prepare informed debate positions.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from lauriemooremoore.com; libguides.fau.edu; kwlibguides.lonestar.edu. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Review primary sources on Texican perspectives during the 1830s.</li><li>Consider economic, cultural, and political motivations.</li><li>Prepare arguments for or against Texican support of independence.</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>A letter from a Texican settler expressing frustration with Mexican trade restrictions illustrates economic motivations.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Formulate a position on whether Texicans were primarily motivated by economic interests or cultural identity in supporting the revolution.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Relying on secondary summaries without engaging with primary source evidence.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> lauriemooremoore.com; libguides.fau.edu; kwlibguides.lonestar.edu <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s6\">[6]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s9\">[9]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s10\">[10]</sup></p>"
