    "eyebrow": "Primary Sources",
    "num": "13",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">13</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Primary Sources</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Land Grants as Windows into Texican Settlement</h2><ul><li>Land grants document official permissions for settlement</li><li>Reveal settler obligations and Mexican government policies</li><li>Provide geographic and demographic data on early Texican communities</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Land grants are foundational primary sources that show how the Mexican government regulated settlement in Texas. They include details on land size, location, and conditions settlers had to meet, offering direct evidence of Texican settlement patterns and legal frameworks. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s9\">[9]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s10\">[10]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s15\">[15]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> A 1825 land grant to an Anglo settler specifies acreage and requires Catholic conversion, illustrating government control over settlement terms.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Examine a sample land grant excerpt and identify key conditions imposed on settlers.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Assuming land grants only reflect settler desires without considering Mexican government intentions.</p></div></div>",
    "paper": {
      "secnum": "Deep Dive 13",
      "h": "Analyzing Land Grants: Legal and Cultural Contexts",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Land grants are foundational primary sources that show how the Mexican government regulated settlement in Texas. They include details on land size, location, and conditions settlers had to meet, offering direct evidence of Texican settlement patterns and legal frameworks.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from libguides.fau.edu; kwlibguides.lonestar.edu; guides.lib.berkeley.edu. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Land grants document official permissions for settlement</li><li>Reveal settler obligations and Mexican government policies</li><li>Provide geographic and demographic data on early Texican communities</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>A 1825 land grant to an Anglo settler specifies acreage and requires Catholic conversion, illustrating government control over settlement terms.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Examine a sample land grant excerpt and identify key conditions imposed on settlers.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Assuming land grants only reflect settler desires without considering Mexican government intentions.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> libguides.fau.edu; kwlibguides.lonestar.edu; guides.lib.berkeley.edu <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s9\">[9]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s10\">[10]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s15\">[15]</sup></p>"
    }
