    "id": "slide38",
    "eyebrow": "Primary Sources",
    "num": "14",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">14</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Primary Sources</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Letters and Personal Correspondence: Insights into Texican Life</h2><ul><li>Reveal personal experiences and perspectives</li><li>Show daily life, challenges, and relationships</li><li>Help corroborate official records with lived realities</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Letters from Texicans provide intimate views of their social, economic, and political lives. These personal documents complement official records by revealing emotions, conflicts, and community dynamics often absent from formal sources. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s11\">[11]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s12\">[12]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s14\">[14]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> A letter from a Texican settler describes tensions with local indigenous groups and frustrations with Mexican authorities, illustrating complex frontier relations.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Analyze a letter excerpt to identify the writer’s main concerns and attitudes toward settlement challenges.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Treating letters as objective facts rather than subjective perspectives influenced by personal bias.</p></div></div>",
