    "id": "slide39",
    "eyebrow": "Primary Sources",
    "num": "15",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">15</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Primary Sources</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Treaties and Agreements: Documenting Texican-Indigenous Relations</h2><ul><li>Formalize peace, trade, or land arrangements</li><li>Reflect power dynamics and negotiation strategies</li><li>Provide evidence of cooperation and conflict</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Treaties between Texicans and Native American tribes are key primary sources that reveal the political and social negotiations shaping frontier life. They document attempts to manage coexistence and territorial claims. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s13\">[13]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s15\">[15]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s16\">[16]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> A treaty with the Caddo tribe outlines boundaries and trade terms, showing efforts to establish peaceful relations amid competing interests.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Identify treaty clauses that indicate concessions or demands from each party.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Assuming treaties were always honored or equally beneficial to all parties.</p></div></div>",
