    "eyebrow": "Primary Sources",
    "num": "16",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">16</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Primary Sources</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Archival Collections: Accessing Texican Historical Records</h2><ul><li>Centralized repositories of diverse primary documents</li><li>Include land grants, letters, treaties, and official records</li><li>Enable comprehensive research and cross-source analysis</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Archival collections gather a wide range of primary sources essential for studying Texican history. They provide access to original documents that allow learners to conduct detailed, evidence-based research. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s9\">[9]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s10\">[10]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s11\">[11]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s12\">[12]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> The Texas State Library archives contain digitized land grants and correspondence from early Texican settlers, facilitating multi-source investigations.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Explore an archival catalog to identify types of documents relevant to Texican history.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Relying on summaries or secondary interpretations without consulting original archival materials.</p></div></div>",
