      "h": "Decoding Treaty Language and Context",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Treaty analysis helps learners understand how language encodes power relations and political intentions in Texican-indigenous agreements.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from libguides.tamusa.edu. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Identify terms favoring each party</li><li>Analyze diplomatic language for implied meanings</li><li>Consider historical context of negotiation</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>A treaty clause granting settlers land use rights while promising indigenous hunting grounds reflects negotiated compromises.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Examine treaty clauses and discuss which party benefits more and why.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Ignoring the political context that shaped treaty terms and enforcement.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> libguides.tamusa.edu <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s13\">[13]</sup></p>"
