    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">20</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Source Evaluation</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Using Archival Catalogs to Locate Texican Documents</h2><ul><li>Learn to navigate archival finding aids and indexes</li><li>Identify relevant document types for research questions</li><li>Understand metadata and document provenance</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Archival catalogs organize vast collections, enabling targeted searches for Texican primary sources. Mastery of these tools is essential for effective historical research. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s9\">[9]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s10\">[10]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Searching a digital archive for 'Texican land grants' yields categorized results with dates, authors, and document summaries.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Use a sample archival catalog to find documents related to Texican settlement policies.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Overlooking metadata details that clarify document context and authenticity.</p></div></div>",
